ot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody">&gt; &gt;    o     Ext2s module now loads<br />&gt; &gt; <br />&gt; &gt; Tried getting this patch through during 1.3; Linus rejected it as making<br />&gt; &gt; it too easy for module to circumvent securelevel.  The fix he wanted was<br />&gt; &gt; write a functional interfaces so that it would be possible for ext2 to<br />&gt; &gt; obtain the current securelevel settings, without being able to set it.<br />&gt; <br />&gt; Garbage reason. You can load a module that patches the kernel if you can <br />&gt; load a module. Securelevel should stop module loads.<br /><br />I don't want to make it _trivial_ to get at the secure-level, and I think it's<br />_wrong_ for a module to depend on it (I broke down and added it anyway, because<br />I haven't gotten the _right_ fix for it, dammit you lazy people!).<br /><br />Not allowing module loads is reasonable, actually. That does NOT change the<br />fact that no module should access "securelevel", which is the original problem.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
